Your Arrival: Reaping Your Rewards

Capstone Project - To the Stars!

In this module, we'll be showing you to how to host your project notebook on Github and then add it into your resume or portfolio. Github is a platform for hosting, managing, and reviewing code. It’s also a very popular platform for hosting personal portfolios, since it’s completely free to create an account.

Step 1: Signup for Github Account

First, if you don't have a Github account already, sign up for one here.

The free plan is more than enough.

Make sure you confirm your email address after creating your account or else Github won't let you do the next step.

Step 2: Create New Repository

Next, click the 'New repository' button. Repositories are like "folders" for storing any files related to a single project or topic.

Set the following settings:

  1. Repository name: Name of your capstone project.
  2. Description: Short description of your project / topic.
  3. Public / Private: Choose public if you'd like to add this project to your resume/portfolio.
  4. Initialize this repository with a README: Check this box.

Then click 'Create repository'.

Step 3: Upload Project Notebook

The typical Github workflow that software engineers use is to use either a command line tool or a desktop tool to sync local folders with Github repositories. If you're familiar with that process, then by all means feel free to continue using it.

But for most people who only want a quick way to host their project online, you can simply manually upload your Jupyter Notebook. It's quick, it's simple, and it gets the job done.

Drag your .ipynb notebook file into the upload box.

Then, write a quick description of your action (e.g. "upload project notebook") and then click 'Commit changes'.

Congrats... you've officially uploaded your project! You can click on your newly uploaded file...

And as you'll see, Github has some built-in tools for rendering your notebook! Not bad!

At this point, you already have a public-facing URL that you can use to share your notebook. While you could technically stop here, the next 2 quick steps will make your notebook and URL look a bit nicer.

Step 4: View Notebook in NBViewer

While Github's built-in notebook rendering tools definitely get the job done, you can make your notebook look a bit prettier by using the nbviewer tool provided by Juptyer.

It's super easy to use. First, copy the full URL of your uploaded notebook on Github. You should already have this up after completing step 3.

Then, head over to nbviewer and paste it into the bar. Press 'Go!'

Now your project should be rendered more cleanly.

Step 5:  Shorten the Link

The final step is to shorten the link so that you can easily include it on your resume if you so choose. There are plenty of URL shorteners out there, but we'll use bit.ly for this module.

First, simply copy the full URL from nbviewer. You should already have this up after completing step 4.

Then, head over to bitly.com. If you want, you can use it directly without creating an account.

However, we recommend creating a free account so that you can customize the link. Otherwise, the shortened link will be a completely random jumble of characters. After creating your account, you can click 'Create' and then paste in the URL from nbviewer. Then, you can customize the title and URL of link.

And that's all! Now you have a shortened, branded link that you can include in your resume or portfolio. For example, our demo shortened is below.

https://bit.ly/eds-capstone-sample

Note: If you're on the Certification Track for the Machine Learning Accelerator, you'll also need that link to acquire the certificate.
